\f4\i present 
\f2\i0 chaos and over-stimulation was regenerated as a place that draws the user knowingly towards a contemplative journey. The Chalet promontory is the intermediate transitory space between the two extremes; the rough urban environment and the pristine underwater silence. An ephemeral, ethereal folly structure, characterized by several layers of steel slats hovers over the existing \'93Chalet\'94 platform. The structure is either perceived as a massive building, or it dissolves partly or completely into the landscape. It provides a spatial experience based on the filtration of the user through an aware-raising experience, providing a 
\f5\i\b remind
\f2\i0\b0 er\cf4  \cf2 of who he is. On the subject of memory, the need was not to reconstruct the past but rather provide a physical reference to it, within the present context, through the use of artificial light. Complete decontextualization happens through the splendor of submergence. From the ephemeral structure and down an offshore path, the visitor is taken through the center of an underwater contemplation place. The calming blue hues of the deep, permit the users to abandon their worries on the surface. The near absence of sound allows the mind to relax and detach completely in a space of nature, body, and mind.}